<subSubSection lastPageId="240" lastPageNumber="241" pageId="239" pageNumber="240" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="239.[151,1436,1850,2019]" lastBlockId="240.[151,1436,151,392]" lastPageId="240" lastPageNumber="241" pageId="239" pageNumber="240">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,440,1851,1874]" pageId="239" pageNumber="240">
Remarks. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[322,440,1851,1874]" italics="true" pageId="239" pageNumber="240">Taxonomy</emphasis>
</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[454,742,1850,1875]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="239" pageNumber="240" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="cabofrioensis">
<emphasis box="[454,742,1850,1875]" italics="true" pageId="239" pageNumber="240">Lissodrillia cabofrioensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a small, glossy species that lacks spiral ornamentation, and has anal sinus that is a deep notch with a divergent outer edge characteristic of 
<taxonomicName box="[1045,1174,1885,1910]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="239" pageNumber="240" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1045,1174,1885,1910]" italics="true" pageId="239" pageNumber="240">Lissodrillia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Its short, low ribs that are reduced in the sulcus are uncharacteristic. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[667,785,1922,1947]" italics="true" pageId="239" pageNumber="240">Variability</emphasis>
. The average length of seven specimens is 
<quantity box="[1271,1371,1922,1946]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.03" pageId="239" pageNumber="240" unit="mm" value="7.03">7.03 mm</quantity>
(
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.95" metricValueMax="7.5" metricValueMin="6.4" pageId="239" pageNumber="240" unit="mm" value="6.95" valueMax="7.5" valueMin="6.4">6.4– 7.5 mm</quantity>
) and average W/L is 
<number box="[505,572,1958,1982]" pageId="239" pageNumber="240" value="0.379">0.379</number>
. Little variability is exhibited by the specimens examined. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1272,1429,1957,1982]" italics="true" pageId="239" pageNumber="240">Identification</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[151,440,1994,2019]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="239" pageNumber="240" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="cabofrioensis">
<emphasis box="[151,440,1994,2019]" italics="true" pageId="239" pageNumber="240">Lissodrillia cabofrioensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[592,778,1994,2019]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Bellaspira" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="239" pageNumber="240" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="rosea" status="new species">
<emphasis box="[592,778,1994,2019]" italics="true" pageId="239" pageNumber="240">Bellaspira rosea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[794,930,1994,2019]" pageId="239" pageNumber="240" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
of the same color and size of a form of that species and taken from the same general area. It can be distinguished from that species by the absence of spiral grooves or threads on the anterior fasciole, its deeper anal sinus, lack of spiral incised lines, and its opisthocline ribs (straight in 
<taxonomicName box="[334,428,224,247]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Bellaspira" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="240" pageNumber="241" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="rosea">
<emphasis box="[334,428,224,247]" italics="true" pageId="240" pageNumber="241">B. rosea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). It is also similar in size and color to a second species in a different genus, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="240" pageNumber="241">
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Cerodrillia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="240" pageNumber="241" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="brasiliensis" status="new species">Cerodrillia brasiliensis</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[294,431,260,285]" pageId="240" pageNumber="241" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but that species has axial ribs extending to the suture, a proportionally large cup-handlelike varix, and spiral ridges on its base and anterior fasciole (
<figureCitation box="[835,931,295,320]" captionStart="PLATE 23" captionStartId="60.[151,234,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[233,1338,195,1820]" captionTargetId="figure@60.[233,1338,195,1820]" captionTargetPageId="60" captionText="PLATE 23. Cerodrillia brasiliensis, new species. Upper panel. Figs. 1 – 3: holotype, off Rio de Janeiro, Brazil (MZSP 122058). Fig. 1: ventral, lateral &amp; dorsal views; Fig. 2: enlarged view of protoconch (not to scale); Fig. 3: apical view, V = varix, L = edge of outer lip. Lower panel. Figs. 4 – 10, 18, 23: paratypes from off Santos São Paulo, Brazil. Figs. 4 – 6: ANSP 464968; Figs. 7 – 9: UF 496634; Figs. 10, 18, 23: MNRJ 34633. Figs. 11 – 17, 19 – 22: paratypes from off Cabo Frio, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil: Fig. 11: MZSP 122059; Figs. 12 – 15, 19: BMSM 14987; Figs. 16, 21: author’s coll.; Figs. 17, 20: MZSP 122059; Fig. 22: MNRJ 34633." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/263322/files/figure.png" pageId="240" pageNumber="241">
Plate 
<number box="[900,931,295,320]" pageId="240" pageNumber="241" value="23.0">23</number>
</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="Jong &amp; Coomans, 1988" authorityName="Jong &amp; Coomans" authorityYear="1988" box="[951,1435,295,320]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Splendrillia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="240" pageNumber="241" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="vinki">
<emphasis box="[951,1145,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="240" pageNumber="241">Splendrillia vinki</emphasis>
(Jong &amp; Coomans, 
<number box="[1370,1427,295,320]" pageId="240" pageNumber="241" value="1988.0">1988</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
is similar, but larger and has more prominent ribs.
</paragraph>
